==English==
===Etymology===
Combination of [[scut]] (a worthless person) and [[work]]
===Noun===
{{en-noun-reg|scutwork}}
# monotonous or menial tasks, usually as part of a larger project.
#:''Has the firm made any effort to provide you with work you are interested in, or have you been more like slave labor to the firm's "dog cases" and '''scutwork'''?'' Robert H Miller, ''Law School Confidential: A Complete Guide to the Law School Experience'' (2004).
#:''Hard to keep that edge of horror over the death of another human being when it was surrounded by so much tedious '''scutwork'''.'' Julia Spencer-Fleming, ''In the Bleak Midwinter'' (2003).
#:''Everyone on a team must pull their fair share of '''scutwork''' if the team is to succeed.'' Harvey Robbins and Michael Finley, ''The New Why Teams Don't Work: What Goes Wrong and How to Make It Right'' (2000).